elements.content: Treatment of [Et4N][Tp*WS3] (1) (Tp* = hydridotris(3,5-dimethylpyrazol-1-yl)borate) with [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6 and NH4PF6 (molar ratio = 1:2:1) in excess pyridine (py) produced one discrete trinuclear cluster [Et4N][Tp*WS3Cu2(py)3](PF6)2 (2). Reactions of 1 with [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6, NH4PF6, and 4,4′-bipyridine (4,4′-bipy) (or 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane (bpea)) (molar ratio = 1:2:1:2) afforded a two-dimensional (2D) [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based cationic polymer {[Tp*WS3Cu2(4,4′-bipy)1.5]­(PF6)·2MeCN} n (3·2MeCN) and a one-dimensional (1D) [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based cationic polymer {[(Tp*WS3Cu2)2(bpea)3]­(PF6)2·2DMF} n (4·2DMF), respectively. Analogous reactions of 1 with CuCN, NH4PF6, and 4,4′-bipy (or 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethylene (bpee)) (molar ratio = 1:2:1:2) gave rise to a 2D [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based polymer {[Tp*WS3Cu2(μ-CN)­(4,4′-bipy)0.5]·MeCN} n (5·MeCN) and a three-dimensional (3D) [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based anionic polymer {[Et4N][(Tp*WS3Cu2)2{Cu(μ-CN)2.5}2­(bpee)]·3MeCN} n (6·3MeCN), respectively. Compounds 2–6 were characterized by elemental analysis, IR, UV–vis, 1H NMR, and single-crystal X-ray diffraction. The cluster cation of 2 has a butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] core structure in which one [Tp*WS3] unit binds two Cu atoms via one μ3-S and two μ-S atoms. 3 consists of one 2D (6,3) network in which butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] units are interlinked by the 4,4′-bipy ligands. 4 contains butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] units that are interconnected by bpea bridges to form one 1D zigzag chain. 5 holds another 2D (6,3) network in which the 1D [{Tp*WS3Cu2}2(μ-CN)2] n chains are bridged by 4,4′-bipy ligands. 6 possesses a 3-connected 3D (103) anionic net in which each 2D [{(Tp*WS3Cu2)2Cu2(μ-CN)4}4­(μ-CN)4(bpee)2] n 4n– network is interlinked to its neighboring ones via pairs of bpee ligands. The isolation of 2–6 with unstable [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores may be ascribed to the coordination of N-donor ligands or linkers at Cu(I) centers of these cores and the formation of polydimensional [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based frameworks (in the case of 3–5). The third-order nonlinear optical (NLO) properties of 2–6 in DMF were also investigated by using a femtosecond degenerate four-wave mixing (DFWM) technique at 800 nm.

elements.content: In the past few decades, the chemistry of Mo/(W)/Cu/S clusters derived from reactions of thiometallate anions [E x MS4–x ]2–, [Cp*MS3]−, and [Tp*MS3]− (Cp* = pentamethylcyclopentadienyl, Tp* = hydridotris(3,5-dimethylpyrazol-1-yl)borate; M = Mo, W; E = O, S; x = 0–2) with CuX (X = Cl, Br, I, NCS, CN) has been extensively investigated because of their interesting structures and their potential applications in biological systems and optoelectronic materials. Theoretically, stepwise addition of one to six Cu(I) atoms onto the S–S edges of the [MS4]2– unit may afford a family of [1 + 1] to [1 + 6] products with a [MS4Cu n ] (n = 1–6) core, while addition of one to three Cu(I) atoms onto the [EMS3] n− (E = O, n = 2; E = Cp* or Tp*, n = 1) unit may form a set of [1 + 1] to [1 + 3] products with a [EMS3Cu n ] (n = 1–3) core. However, such stepwise addition reactions were difficult to achieve because the [1 + 3] products like incomplete cubanelike [EMS3Cu3] clusters or complete cubanelike [EMS3Cu3X] clusters were always isolated. Only a few examples were reported to produce the [1 + 2] products with a so-called butterfly-shaped [EMS3Cu2] core such as [Et4N][Tp*WS3­(CuSCN)2], [Cp*WS3Cu2(PPh3)­(μ-CN)]2, and so on. Generally, such a butterfly-shaped core is not stable and tends to have one more Cu(I) added onto its framework to form incomplete or complete cubanelike structures. Considering that many M/Cu/S-based coordination polymers could be generated via using various nitrogen donor ligands, is it possible to employ these donor ligands to stabilize such unstable [EMS3Cu2] cores accompanied by the formation of the corresponding [EMS3Cu2]-supported coordination polymers? With this question in mind, we deliberately selected four N-donor ligands: a terminal ligand pyridine (py), two rigid bidentate ligands (4,4′-bipyridine (4,4′-bipy) and 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethylene (bpee)), and a flexible ligand 1,2-bis(4-pyridyl)ethane (bpea) (Scheme ), and carried out the reactions of [Et4N][Tp*WS3] (1) with 2 equiv of [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6 or CuCN and these N-donor ligands in the presence of NH4PF6. Five novel [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based coordination compounds, [Et4N][Tp*WS3Cu2(py)3]­(PF6)2 (2), {[Tp*WS3Cu2(4,4′-bipy)1.5]­(PF6)} n (3), {[(Tp*WS3Cu2)2(bpea)3]­(PF6)2} n (4), {[Tp*WS3Cu2(μ-CN)­(4,4′-bipy)0.5]} n (5), and {[Et4N][(Tp*WS3Cu2)2­{Cu(μ-CN)2.5}2(bpee)]} n (6) were isolated therefrom. On the other hand, many Mo(W)/Cu/S clusters, especially those incomplete or complete cubanelike [EWS3Cu3] clusters, are known to possess good third-order nonlinear optical (NLO) performances. However, those with butterfly-shaped [EWS3Cu2] cores seem less explored due to their limitation in number. We thus measured their third-order NLO properties in DMF by using the femtosecond degenerate four-wave mixing (DFWM) technique with 80 fs pulse width at 800 nm and found that they exhibited better NLO performances than 1. In this paper, we report their syntheses, structures, and third-order NLO properties.

Materials and Methods

General Procedure

All manipulations were performed under an argon atmosphere using standard Schlenk-line techniques. Compound 1 was prepared as reported previously. All solvents were predried over activated molecular sieves and refluxed over the appropriate drying agents under argon. IR spectra were recorded on a Varian 1000 FT-IR spectrometer as KBr disks (4000-400 cm-1). Electronic spectra were measured on a Varian 50 spectrophotometer. Elemental analyses for C, H, and N were performed on a Carlo-Erba CHNO-S microanalyzer. 1H NMR spectra were recorded at ambient temperature on a Varain UNITYplus-400 spectrometer. The 1H NMR chemical shifts were referenced to TMS in CDCl3 or to the deuterated dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO-d 6) signal.

elements.content: As reported previously, reactions of [Et4N][Tp*WS3(CuBr)3] with py or aniline (ani) and NH4PF6 afforded a cationic cluster [Tp*WS3Cu3(py)3(μ3-Br)](PF6) and a neutral cluster [{Tp*WS3(CuBr)3}(μ6-Br){Tp*WS3Cu3(ani)3}]. The formation of these two clusters suggested that the presence of NH4PF6 might be beneficial to the assembly of Mo(W)/Cu/S clusters. Thus we also introduced NH4PF6 into the above-mentioned reaction systems. Upon addition of equimolar NH4PF6, the reactions of 1 with [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6 (molar ratio = 1:1:2) in excess pyridine could generate 2 in a higher yield (67%), while analogous reactions of 1 with [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6 (or CuCN), 4,4′-bipy (or bpee or bpea) and NH4PF6 (molar ratio = 1:2:2:1) successfully produced 3 (47% yield) and 4 (33% yield), 5 (46% yield) and 6 (41% yield), respectively. However, reactions of 1 with [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6 and bpee and those of 1 with CuCN and bpea even in the presence of NH4PF6 still afforded a large amount of red insoluble precipitates, whose chemical formulas were tentatively assumed to be [Tp*WS3Cu2(bpee)](PF6) and [(Tp*WS3Cu2)2(CN)2(bpea)] based on their elemental analysis and X-ray fluorescence analysis. As described later in this article, compounds 2–6 all contain unstable butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores in their structures. The existence of these unstable cluster cores may be ascribed to carefully controlling the 1:2:2:1 molar ratio of 1/Cu(I) salt/N-donor ligand/NH4PF6 and the N-donor ligands stabilizing these cores via their coordination at their Cu(I) centers and the formation of various polydimensional [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported supramolecular architectures.

elements.content: Compounds 2 and 4 were soluble in common solvents such as MeCN, CH2Cl2, CHCl3, DMF, and DMSO, while 3, 5, and 6 were slightly soluble in DMF and DMSO. The elemental analyses were consistent with the chemical formulas of 2–6. In the IR spectra of 2–6, bands at 408 (2), 430 (3), 427 (4), 423 (5), 415 (6) cm–1 were assigned as the bridging W–S stretching vibrations. The spectra also showed the B–H stretching vibrations at ca. 2558 cm–1 and the pyrazolyl rings at ca. 1545, 1450, and 1415 cm–1, while bands at 2098 (5) and 2096 (6) cm–1 were assigned to be the CN stretching vibrations. The UV–vis spectra of 2–6 in DMF were characterized by two bands (Figure ). Relative to the band at 323 nm (2), those at 314 nm (3) and (4), 317 nm (5), and 309 nm (6) were slightly blue-shifted, and they were probably dominated by the S → W(VI) charge-transfer transitions of the [Tp*WS3] moiety. In their 1H NMR spectra of 2–6, the B–H protons were not located. elements.content: Compound 4·2DMF crystallizes in the monoclinic space group P21/c, and the asymmetric unit contains half a [(Tp*WS3Cu2)2(bpea)3]2+ dication, one PF6 – anion, and one DMF solvent molecule. The cluster dication in 4 shows a dimeric structure in which two butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] fragments are connected with a pair of bpea bridges (Figure a). There is a crystallographic inversion center lying at the midpoint of the W1 and W1A contact. For each [Tp*WS3Cu2] fragment in 4, Cu(1) is tetrahedrally coordinated by one μ-S, one μ3-S, and two N from two bpea ligands, while Cu(2) adopts a trigonal planar geometry, coordinated by one μ-S, one μ3-S, and one N from the bpea ligand. The W···Cu contacts [2.6029(9) Å vs. 2.6468(9) Å] in 4 are comparable to those of the corresponding ones of 3. The Cu1···Cu2 contact (2.822 Å) is almost the same as that of 3. The W-μ-S, W-μ3-S, Cu-μ3-S, Cu-μ-S, and Cu–N bond lengths are also normal. Each dimeric [(Tp*WS3Cu2)2(bpea)3]2+ dication is further connected to its equivalent ones via two bpea ligands to form a 1D zigzag chain extending along the c axis (Figure b), which is similar to that observed in {[(Cp*MoS3Cu3)2­(μ-bpea)3Br4]­·DMSO·3MeCN} n . Topologically, this 1D chain may be viewed as being built of [Tp*WS3Cu2] fragments as an angular two-connecting node (node (b) in Scheme ) that are interconnected by one single bridge and one double bpea bridge. Each bpea ligand in 4 presents as a trans-trans conformation. There is a weak π···π interaction between the pyridyl rings of the two neighboring bpea ligands with a distance of 3.949(2) Å, while the dihedral angle between the two pyridyl rings is 17.4(2)° (calculated by the Platon program). However, the π···π interaction between the pyridyl rings of the two neighboring bpea ligands in {[(Cp*MoS3Cu3)2­(μ-bpea)3Br4]­·DMSO·3MeCN} n is much weaker (4.154(2) Å) and the dihedral angle between the two pyridyl rings is 35.59(2)°.

The Cu1···Cu2 contact (2.811 Å) is the same as those of 3 and 4. The Cu3 atom in each [Cu(μ-CN)3(bpee)]2– is tetrahedrally coordinated with three μ-CN and one bpee ligand. Compared to those copper(I) cyanide linkers previously reported such as [Cu(μ-CN)3]2– observed in [Tp*WS3Cu3(μ3-DMF)­{Cu(μ-CN)3}]2 and [Cu4(μ-CN)9]5– in K[Tp*WS3Cu3­(μ3-DMF){Cu2(μ-CN)4.5}]2, the [Cu(μ-CN)3(bpee)]2– species in 6, both having three cyanides and one bpee ligand coordinated at one Cu(I) center, would be an uncommon metalloligand linker. From a topological view, each [Tp*WS3Cu2] core may be regarded as an angular 2-connecting node (node (b) in Scheme ), while Cu3 works as a 3-connecting node (node (c) in Scheme ). Four [(Tp*WS3Cu2)2Cu2(μ-CN)4] macrometallocycles, four cyanides, two bpee ligands, and two extra Cu3 atoms are combined to form a 66-membered [{(Tp*WS3Cu2)2­Cu2(μ-CN)4}4­(bpee)2Cu2(μ-CN)4] ring (Figure b). This ring is further linked by cyanide bridges to afford a 2D [{(Tp*WS3Cu2)2­Cu2(μ-CN)4}4­(μ-CN)4(bpee)2] n 4n– anionic network extending along the [2,1,1] plane (Figure c). Such a 2D layer is interconnected to its neighboring ones via bpee ligands, thereby generating a 3-connected 3D net with a Schlafli symbol of 103 (Figure d).

Crystal Structure of 6⋅3MeCN

Compound 6⋅3MeCN crystallizes in the monoclinic space group C2/c, and its asymmetric unit contains half a [(Tp*WS3Cu2)2{Cu(μ-CN)2.5}2(bpee)]- anion and half a [Et4N]+ cation. This anion contains two butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2] fragments linked by two [Cu(μ-CN)3(bpee)]2- species via four cyanide bridges to form a centrosymmetric macrometallocycle [(Tp*WS3Cu2)2Cu2(μ-CN)4(bpee)2] (Figure a). In each butterfly-shaped fragment, each Cu atom is trigonally coordinated by one μ-S, one μ3-S, and one N (or C) of one cyanide. The mean W1⋅⋅⋅Cu contact (2.6397(13) Å) is longer than those of the corresponding ones in 2-4. The Cu3 atom in each [Cu(μ-CN)3(bpee)]2- is tetrahedrally coordinated with three μ-CN and one bpee ligand. Compared to those copper(I) cyanide linkers previously reported such as [Cu(μ-CN)3]2- observed in [Tp*WS3Cu3(μ3-DMF){Cu(μ-CN)3}]2 and [Cu4(μ-CN)9]5- in K[Tp*WS3Cu3(μ3-DMF){Cu2(μ-CN)4.5}]2, the [Cu(μ-CN)3(bpee)]2- species in 6, both having three cyanides and one bpee ligand coordinated at one Cu(I) center, would be an uncommon metalloligand linker. From a topological view, each [Tp*WS3Cu2] core may be regarded as an angular 2-connecting node (node (b) in Scheme ), while Cu3 works as a 3-connecting node (node (c) in Scheme ). Four [(Tp*WS3Cu2)2Cu2(μ-CN)4] macrometallocycles, four cyanides, two bpee ligands, and two extra Cu3 atoms are combined to form a 66-membered [{(Tp*WS3Cu2)2Cu2(μ-CN)4}4(bpee)2Cu2(μ-CN)4] ring (Figure b). This ring is further linked by cyanide bridges to afford a 2D [{(Tp*WS3Cu2)2Cu2(μ-CN)4}4(μ-CN)4(bpee)2] n  4n- anionic network extending along the [2,1,1] plane (Figure c). Such a 2D layer is interconnected to its neighboring ones via bpee ligands, thereby generating a 3-connected 3D net with a Schlafli symbol of 103 (Figure d).

Third-Order Nonlinear Optical (NLO) Properties of 2-6 

As indicated in Figure , the electronic spectra of 2-6 in DMF showed relatively low linear absorption at 800 nm. The laser wavelength (800 nm) used in the NLO experiment was out of the absorption region, which guaranteed low intensity loss and little temperature change by photon absorption during the NLO measurements. Thus, the off-resonant third-order optical nonlinearities of the title compounds could be determined. The nonlinear absorption effects of 2-6 in DMF were evaluated by the femtosecond degenerate four-wave mixing (DFWM) technique with 80 fs pulse width at 800 nm (Figure  and Figures S2-S5, ). Although the detailed mechanism is still unknown, the NLO absorption data obtained under the conditions used in this study can be evaluated from the reported methods (). The third-order nonlinear optical susceptibility χ(3) can be calculated to be 5.1 × 10-14 esu (2), 3.4 × 10-14 esu (3), 4.2 × 10-14 esu (4), 3.1 × 10-14 esu (5), and 6.4 × 10-14 esu (6). The effective third-order NLO refractive indexes n 2 are 2.0 × 10-12 esu (2), 1.5 × 10-12 esu (3), 1.8 × 10-12 esu (4), 1.4 × 10-12 esu (5), and 2.2 × 10-12 esu (6). The effective third-order NLO refractive indexes n 2 are positive, suggesting that they all possessed strong self-focusing effect. The results showed that they possess relatively strong third-order optical nonlinearities in solution.

In this paper, we have demonstrated the assembly of a set of butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported clusters 2–6 from reactions of 1 with 2 equiv of [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6 or CuCN and four N-donor ligands in the presence of NH4PF6. 2 has a simple cationic [Tp*WS3Cu2] structure. 3 and 5 possess two different types of 2D (6,3) [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based networks in which [Tp*WS3Cu2] units are interlinked by 4,4′-bipy bridges (3) or a combination of cyanides and 4,4′-bipy bridges (5). 4 has a 1D [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported bpea-bridged zigzag chain. 6 possesses a 3-connected 3D (103) anionic [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based net in which [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores are linked by cyanide and bpee bridges in [Cu(μ-CN)3(bpee)]2– species. 2–6 all contain the unstable [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores in their structures, and their successful assembly may be ascribed to the following three reasons: stoichiometrically controlling 1:2:2:1 molar ratio of 1/Cu(I) salt/N-donor ligand/NH4PF6, stabilizing these cores by coordination of N-donor ligands at Cu(I) centers, and forming 1D to 3D [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based supramolcular frameworks (except for 2). In addition, the solutions of 2–6 exhibited good third-order NLO responses, and their γ values are greatly improved, being 26.4–33.6 times larger than that of 1. This improvement could be due to the formation of [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores in 2–6 and possibly due to the peripheral ligands surrounding the cluster cores and the aforementioned cluster-based supramolecular frameworks (in the cases of 3–5). It is anticipated that the synthetic methodology reported here could be applied in the rational assembly of novel cluster-based arrays with more intriguing structures and better NLO performances from reactions of 1 with coin metal salts (e.g., Cu(I), Ag(I), Au(I)) and other multidentate N-donor ligands such as 2,4,6-tri(4-pyridyl)-1,3,5-triazine and 1,1,3,3-tetrakis(3,5-dimethyl-1-pyrazole)propane. Studies in this respect are underway in this laboratory.

Conclusions

In this paper, we have demonstrated the assembly of a set of butterfly-shaped [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported clusters 2-6 from reactions of 1 with 2 equiv of [Cu(MeCN)4]PF6 or CuCN and four N-donor ligands in the presence of NH4PF6. 2 has a simple cationic [Tp*WS3Cu2] structure. 3 and 5 possess two different types of 2D (6,3) [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based networks in which [Tp*WS3Cu2] units are interlinked by 4,4'-bipy bridges (3) or a combination of cyanides and 4,4'-bipy bridges (5). 4 has a 1D [Tp*WS3Cu2]-supported bpea-bridged zigzag chain. 6 possesses a 3-connected 3D (103) anionic [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based net in which [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores are linked by cyanide and bpee bridges in [Cu(μ-CN)3(bpee)]2- species. 2-6 all contain the unstable [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores in their structures, and their successful assembly may be ascribed to the following three reasons: stoichiometrically controlling 1:2:2:1 molar ratio of 1/Cu(I) salt/N-donor ligand/NH4PF6, stabilizing these cores by coordination of N-donor ligands at Cu(I) centers, and forming 1D to 3D [Tp*WS3Cu2]-based supramolcular frameworks (except for 2). In addition, the solutions of 2-6 exhibited good third-order NLO responses, and their γ values are greatly improved, being 26.4-33.6 times larger than that of 1. This improvement could be due to the formation of [Tp*WS3Cu2] cores in 2-6 and possibly due to the peripheral ligands surrounding the cluster cores and the aforementioned cluster-based supramolecular frameworks (in the cases of 3-5). It is anticipated that the synthetic methodology reported here could be applied in the rational assembly of novel cluster-based arrays with more intriguing structures and better NLO performances from reactions of 1 with coin metal salts (e.g., Cu(I), Ag(I), Au(I)) and other multidentate N-donor ligands such as 2,4,6-tri(4-pyridyl)-1,3,5-triazine and 1,1,3,3-tetrakis(3,5-dimethyl-1-pyrazole)propane. Studies in this respect are underway in this laboratory.

The effective third-order NLO refractive indexes n 2 are positive, suggesting that they all possessed strong self-focusing effect. As indicated in Figure , the electronic spectra of 2-6 in DMF showed relatively low linear absorption at 800 nm. The laser wavelength (800 nm) used in the NLO experiment was out of the absorption region, which guaranteed low intensity loss and little temperature change by photon absorption during the NLO measurements. Thus, the off-resonant third-order optical nonlinearities of the title compounds could be determined. The nonlinear absorption effects of 2-6 in DMF were evaluated by the femtosecond degenerate four-wave mixing (DFWM) technique with 80 fs pulse width at 800 nm (Figure  and Figures S2-S5, ). Although the detailed mechanism is still unknown, the NLO absorption data obtained under the conditions used in this study can be evaluated from the reported methods (). The third-order nonlinear optical susceptibility χ(3) can be calculated to be 5.1 × 10-14 esu (2), 3.4 × 10-14 esu (3), 4.2 × 10-14 esu (4), 3.1 × 10-14 esu (5), and 6.4 × 10-14 esu (6). The effective third-order NLO refractive indexes n 2 are positive, suggesting that they all possessed strong self-focusing effect. The results showed that they possess relatively strong third-order optical nonlinearities in solution.
